Intro

By the time a country is well developed, its growth in population can change dramatically. What features have strong relations with population growth? How would I go about testing that?

Before starting any data science project, the first thing we have to do is is gather and understand the data we are working with. In this case, I will be using data for from The world bank world development indicators database downloaded as a csv. http://databank.worldbank.org/data/reports.aspx?source=world-development-indicators# 2 files were provided, one that provides a description to generated column names and the other the main dataset.Both csv’s were renamed before reading. The main data used in this project was national income, population growth by percent, total population, access to water, electricity access, and access to the internet. The countries eventually focused on were Russia, China, United States, India, United Kingdom, Japan, and Nigeria. The data spanned from 1993 to 2018.

In order to read this data, we need to access the csv. I can use the read_csv function from readr. how well can statistics like water access, gross national income, and other stuff correlate with carbon dioxiode damage, 20$ of environmental damage per tone. use hypothesis test to show it.

Tidying

I now need to clean this data. There a few things I need to do. First, I should rename the Series code column to be reader friendly, then make the dataset tidy. This means that the data should have the following:
1. Each attribute(Ex, year) forms a column
2. Each entity(observation) forms a row
3. Each type of entity forms a table. This means that there rent multiple tables of different entities joined for no reason.
With our current dataset, multiple years are spanned across columns, and different types of information such as income and percentages are stored in the same column. Tidying data is useful to do before data cleaning. The dplyr library is used for dataset manipulation.

library(dplyr)
#this part is just for renaming purposes, specifically columns with spaces
renamedPopulation <- populationData %>%
  rename(Code = `Series Code`, Country = `Country Code`, CountryName = `Country Name`) %>%
  select(-`Series Name`, -`2017 [YR2017]`) %>%
  filter(CountryName == "United States"| CountryName == "China"| CountryName == "India" | CountryName == "Nigeria" | CountryName == "Japan" | CountryName == "United Kingdom" | CountryName == "Russian Federation")

#now I create a table for each different entity type (code) in this case
electricAccess <- renamedPopulation %>%
  filter(Code == "EG.ELC.ACCS.ZS") %>%
  select(-Code)

internetAccess <- renamedPopulation %>%
  filter(Code == "IT.NET.USER.ZS") %>%

waterAccess <- renamedPopulation %>%

From the above code:
- rename renames the column names with spaces, this made the table easier to read.
- select(-attribute) selects the whole dataframe except for that attribute.
- filter is a conditional that returns all rows that accept the conditional
- Gather: A good way to think about gather is that every column not included(denoted with -) is exempt from getting merged into the gathered column. In this case, that gathered column is Year and its values were the values found under the year columns.
- mutate is used to modify or a column. as.integer((unlist(strsplit(Year, " “))[1])) first splits the column with strsplit which returns a list Then unlist turns the list to a vector. This allows me to get the actual year, the first element from the split [1]. as.integer converts the string to an integer.

The tables are almost tidy, but this table can still be split up into different tables.

library(tidyr)
#Running this section more than once will break the tables unless you run from the beginning
electricAccess <- electricAccess %>% gather(Year, ElectricityAccessPercentage, -CountryName, -Country)%>%
  mutate("Year" = as.integer(substring(Year, 1, 4))) %>%
  mutate("ElectricityAccessPercentage" = as.double(ElectricityAccessPercentage))

internetAccess <-internetAccess %>% gather(Year, InternetAccessPercentage, -CountryName, -Country)%>%

There is some important information we can see from these general charts. We can see that it looks like having a high access to electricity possibly follows lower population growth. However, the electricity data is missing some values, specifically data from Russia, Japan, and The United Kingdom. This data is missing systematically, as it looks like no measurements were taken at all in those countries. Because so much is missing, this dataset will be avoided.

The drinkable water dataset doesn’t start until 2000, and within that, the US doesn’t start recording until 2005. Looking at the data, it does seem linear, so I will estimate the unknown values with a linear model. Because water levels across different countries do not seem to have any relation with each other, I will use linear regression with water access regressed on Year for each country.

#function used to predict the empty values
estimateWaterValues <- function(cName, waterDF){
  
  waterPredictor <- waterDF %>%
    filter(CountryName == cName) %>%
    lm(WaterAccessPercentage~Year, data = .)

  waterDF <- waterDF %>%
    modelr::add_predictions(waterPredictor, var="tempPrediction")

  waterDF <- waterDF %>%
    mutate("WaterAccessPercentage" = ifelse(!is.na(WaterAccessPercentage), WaterAccessPercentage, ifelse(CountryName == cName ,  tempPrediction, NA) )) %>%
    select(-tempPrediction)
  
  return(waterDF)
}
waterAccess <- estimateWaterValues("United States", waterAccess)
waterAccess <- estimateWaterValues("China", waterAccess)
waterAccess <- estimateWaterValues("Japan", waterAccess)
waterAccess <- estimateWaterValues("India", waterAccess)
waterAccess <- estimateWaterValues("Nigeria", waterAccess)
waterAccess <- estimateWaterValues("Russian Federation", waterAccess)
waterAccess <- estimateWaterValues("United Kingdom", waterAccess)

library(ggplot2)
tplot <-  waterAccess %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Year, y=WaterAccessPercentage)) +
  labs(title="Access to Drinkable Water With Estimations",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Percent Access") + 
  geom_point(aes(color = CountryName)) + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=scales::pretty_breaks(n = 5))
tplot

internetAccess <- internetAccess %>%

EDA

After this visual analysis, I can now check for relationships between what we are testing, population growth and the other data. The parameters I can test are: -Year
-Population Growth
-Access to Water
-Access to the Internet
-Total Population

Because the tidy tables from earlier were all based on year and country, I was able to join them all seamlessly.

combinedTidyDF = nationalIncome %>%
  inner_join(populationTotal)  %>%
  inner_join(populationGrowth)   %>%
  inner_join(waterAccess)  %>%
  inner_join(internetAccess)

To test some models for relationships between data, I will be using linear regression. First, we test if any of the predictors have a significant relationship with the data.

Now do the regression.

We can use a linear model to figure out how well the parameters correspond with the population growth percentage. We can use hypothesis testing to figure this out. Broom tidy is used to tidy the data and show relvant information for hypothesis testing.

incomePopGrowthModel <- lm(formula = PopulationGrowthPercentage ~ Income, combinedTidyDF)
tidyincomePopGrowthModel <- broom::tidy(incomePopGrowthModel)
tidyincomePopGrowthModel

From the linear models, the null hypothesis was not significant for income, access to water, and internet access. However, there was a statistically significant relationship between population growth percentage with parameters year. These P-values might also mean that the data is not linearly related, in which case, the p-values could be erratic.
